The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, April 7: Reserve Bank governor D. Subbarao will meet heads of leading Indian banks here tomorrow to discuss the emerging situation in the banking industry. The governor is likely to ask the banks to ensure adequate credit flow to productive sectors such as the small and medium enterprises, besides further reduction in banks lending rates, the head of a leading public-sector bank said.                            
	 Chennai, April 7: Renowned economist Raja J. Chelliah died today after a brief illness. He was instrumental in bringing in tax reforms in the early 1990s. Chelliah was the chairman of the tax reforms committee between 1991 and 1993. He contributed significantly to fiscal policies post-liberalisation in the country.                            
	 London, April 7: British banking major, the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS), will slash 9,000 jobs worldwide in the coming days, including 4,500 positions in the UK, as part of its cost-cutting measures. The move will affect the banks manufacturing roles, which consists mainly of back office operations.                            
	 New Delhi, April 7: Air India will get the delivery of its first Boeing 787 Dreamliner aircraft by June 2010. This will enable the carrier to have more long-haul international flights. It will enter into service in the first quarter of calendar 2010 with Japans All Nippon Airways as its launch customer.                            
	 New Delhi, April 7: Essar Steel plans to start the first phase of production from its proposed $1.1-billion steel plant at Minnesota in the US by 2011. In the second phase, a slab-making unit would also come up.                             
	 New Delhi, April 7: PowerGrid Corp will borrow $2 billion (about Rs 10,000 crore) from the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank to part finance Rs 55,000-crore investment plans till 2012.                             
	 New Delhi, April 7: Over 1.30 lakh Indian entrepreneurs, mainly in the small and medium sectors, have sought relief from government-owned banks, which have completed corporate debt restructuring worth Rs 14,000 crore till February.                                                                                                                           
